
[1]viaticum

   VIAT'ICUM, n. [L. supra.]

   1. Provisions for a journey.

   2. Among the ancient Romans, an allowance to officers who were sent
   into the provinces to exercise any office or perform any service, also
   to the officers and soldiers of the army.

   3. In the Romish church, the communion or eucharist given to persons in
   their last moment.
